From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
Subject: [PATCH] Zero the inlined buffer in string_t(uint32_t len)

Valgrind reports "Conditional jump or move depends on uninitialised
value(s)" in StringValueComparison (string_stats.cpp:125/127), reached
from StringStats::Update during the StatisticsPropagator's constant
folding for a VARIANT -> STRUCT -> STRING value. The trace identifies
the originating "stack allocation" as the PLT entry for
StringVector::EmptyString.

StringVector::EmptyString returns `string_t(UnsafeNumericCast<uint32_t>(len))`
for inlined strings (len <= INLINE_LENGTH). The `string_t(uint32_t len)`
constructor only writes the 4-byte length and leaves the 12-byte inlined
buffer indeterminate. Callers (e.g. the to_variant cast) then write
`len` bytes into the buffer via GetDataWriteable() and finally call
SetSizeAndFinalize, which calls Finalize() to zero the trailing
bytes from `len` to INLINE_BYTES.

In practice the buffer is fully written by the time the value is
consumed, but the 16-byte string_t is bitwise-copied around (assignment
in the FlatVector slot, the temporary string_t constructed in
StringStats::Update via `string_t(string_value)`, the local `target[8]`
filled by ConstructValue) before every byte has been written. valgrind
follows the propagation of those indeterminate bytes from the moment
they appear on the stack and flags the comparison in
StringValueComparison.

Initialise the inlined buffer in the length-only constructor. This is
the same defensive treatment the (const char *, uint32_t) constructor
already applies to its inlined case, and matches what Finalize() does
once the caller is done writing.
---
 src/duckdb/src/include/duckdb/common/types/string_type.hpp | 8 ++++++++
 1 file changed, 8 insertions(+)

diff --git a/src/duckdb/src/include/duckdb/common/types/string_type.hpp b/src/duckdb/src/include/duckdb/common/types/string_type.hpp
--- a/src/duckdb/src/include/duckdb/common/types/string_type.hpp
+++ b/src/duckdb/src/include/duckdb/common/types/string_type.hpp
@@ -40,6 +40,13 @@ struct string_t {
 	string_t() = default;
 	explicit string_t(uint32_t len) {
 		value.inlined.length = len;
+		// Zero the inlined buffer. Callers (e.g. StringVector::EmptyString) hand
+		// the resulting string_t to write paths that fill `len` bytes and then
+		// call Finalize(); the unfilled trailing bytes need to be defined so
+		// that copies of the string_t (e.g. through a constant VARIANT BLOB
+		// flowing into StringStats::Update during constant folding) do not
+		// propagate indeterminate bytes.
+		memset(value.inlined.inlined, 0, INLINE_BYTES);
 	}
 	string_t(const char *data, uint32_t len) {
 		value.inlined.length = len;
--
2.52.0
